    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_38028014" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/38028014" />
    <a title="Dale" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/329383-dale"><img alt="Dale" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1448977473p2/329383.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/38028014?book_show_action=true">Nov 18, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Dale" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Dale" href="/user/show/329383-dale">Dale</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer38028014&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer38028014" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7501045403348158824">I am a self-avowed suckers for happy endings, even when they are a little contrived or a little too pat. So it&apos;s not really surprising that Q&amp;A would hold up well for me, because the whole premise of the book is all about pat contrivances and happy endings. The book opens with the arrest of the narrator, Ram, who has just won a billion rupees on an Indian game show; the producers believe he must have cheated to answer all of the questions correctly. He is rescued from brutal police interrogation</span>
  <span id="freeText7501045403348158824" style="display:none">I am a self-avowed suckers for happy endings, even when they are a little contrived or a little too pat. So it's not really surprising that Q&amp;A would hold up well for me, because the whole premise of the book is all about pat contrivances and happy endings. The book opens with the arrest of the narrator, Ram, who has just won a billion rupees on an Indian game show; the producers believe he must have cheated to answer all of the questions correctly. He is rescued from brutal police interrogation by an altruistic young lawyer who intends to defend him against the cheating charges - all she needs is to understand how he knew the answers. So Ram tells his life story in snippets, focusing on the formative moments of his childhood which happened to give him the information he would be quizzed on in front of a t.v. studio audience. It's a bit of a Picaresque adventure as Ram goes from an orphanage to a rectory to the homes of the wealthy and powerful (as a servant) to a ghetto apartment to the Taj Mahal (as a tour guide) to tending bar in the ghetto. As fate would have it, in each of those places he learns some obscure trivia which comes in miraculously handy on the quiz show. In my mind that's a make-or-break premise - if you can swallow it, you'll really enjoy the book, and if it seems too far-fetched, the book will probably annoy you to no end. I found it to be right up my alley - I like looking for the little connections in life and I could read about how living next to an alcoholic former astronomy professor whose daughter named a kitten after Pluto because Pluto is the smallest planet leads to an illiterate boy knowing which is the smallest planet (but not how many planets there are) all day.<br /><br />The brilliant thing about the book is that the ending has multiple plot twists and revelations of its own, tangential to the central question of whether or not the lawyer will help Ram get his billion rupees the producers are trying to renege on. And those revelations are highly coincidental and unlikely in and of themselves, but with the groundwork the book lays beforehand in making coincidences seem commonplace, it all feels right (if a bit rushed).<br /><br />Most importantly, Ram is a great protagonist, likable and virtuous and very easy to root for, so it's genuinely gratifying to see the stars align for him. Horrific things happen to him and all around him throughout his life, but his story was never too painful to be witness to. And, for a sucker like me, his well-deserved happy ending was sweet reward.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7501045403348158824" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


